<div class="prose">

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">📌 Why these words?</div>
  <p>This unit asks you to design a 100 km² Sustainable Land Plan optimizing across multiple objectives — yield, biodiversity, carbon, equity, livelihoods. You will defend your plan to a Regional Planning Board. The vocabulary below is the working language of land-use planning and ecology.</p>
</div>

<h2>Vocabulary</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Term</th>
      <th>What it means + visual cue</th>
      <th>Sentence stem</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Biodiversity</strong></td>
      <td>The variety of life in a place — species, genetic diversity, ecosystem types. <em>Visual: Multiple plant and animal silhouettes in one frame.</em></td>
      <td>Biodiversity in this region is ___ because ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Ecosystem services</strong></td>
      <td>The benefits humans get from ecosystems — clean water, pollination, carbon storage, flood control, recreation. <em>Visual: Forest with arrows pointing to water, food, oxygen, climate.</em></td>
      <td>A key ecosystem service in this region is ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Carbon sequestration</strong></td>
      <td>The process of capturing CO₂ from the atmosphere and storing it in plants, soil, or wood. Forests, wetlands, and grasslands all sequester carbon. <em>Visual: Tree pulling CO₂ down into roots and soil.</em></td>
      <td>Carbon sequestration potential here is ___ because ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Land cover</strong></td>
      <td>What physically covers the land — forest, grassland, cropland, urban, wetland, bare. Different from land USE (how it is managed). <em>Visual: Patchwork map with color-coded land cover types.</em></td>
      <td>Current land cover in this region is ___% forest, ___% cropland, ___% other.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Agroforestry</strong></td>
      <td>Combining trees with crops or livestock on the same land. Yields, biodiversity, and carbon all benefit. <em>Visual: Field with rows of crops between rows of trees.</em></td>
      <td>Agroforestry in this plan would mean ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Monoculture</strong></td>
      <td>Growing a single crop over a large area. Productive but vulnerable to pests and biodiversity-poor. <em>Visual: Vast field of identical crop rows stretching to horizon.</em></td>
      <td>Monoculture in this region creates ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Fragmentation</strong></td>
      <td>When continuous habitat is broken into smaller, disconnected patches by roads, fields, or development. Harms many species. <em>Visual: Forest cut by a road into separated patches.</em></td>
      <td>Fragmentation in this plan is reduced / increased by ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Restoration</strong></td>
      <td>Returning a degraded ecosystem to a functional state — replanting, removing dams, rewilding. <em>Visual: Bare ground next to the same plot after replanting.</em></td>
      <td>Restoration in this plan would target ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Succession</strong></td>
      <td>The natural change of plant and animal communities over time after a disturbance. Bare ground → grass → shrubs → trees. <em>Visual: Time arrow showing landscape progressing from bare to forested.</em></td>
      <td>Succession in this plan is allowed / accelerated by ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Trade-off</strong></td>
      <td>When improving one objective worsens another. The core of multi-objective planning. <em>Visual: Seesaw with two competing objectives.</em></td>
      <td>A trade-off in my plan is ___ vs. ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Multi-objective optimisation</strong></td>
      <td>Designing for several goals at once, accepting that no single solution maximizes all. Find the best balance. <em>Visual: Spider/radar chart with multiple axes.</em></td>
      <td>My plan optimises across ___, ___, and ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Conservation</strong></td>
      <td>Protecting natural habitats and species from degradation or loss. Different from preservation (no use at all). <em>Visual: Fenced reserve with a "protected" sign.</em></td>
      <td>Conservation in this plan covers ___% of the area.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Indigenous land use</strong></td>
      <td>Land management traditions developed by Indigenous communities over generations, often highly sustainable. <em>Visual: Hand passing seed across multiple generations.</em></td>
      <td>Indigenous land use in this region historically meant ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Yield</strong></td>
      <td>The amount of crop, timber, or product produced per unit area. Important but only one of several objectives. <em>Visual: Grain harvest in a measured field.</em></td>
      <td>Yield in this scenario is ___ tonnes per hectare.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Livelihood</strong></td>
      <td>The means by which people make a living. Land plans that ignore livelihoods rarely succeed politically. <em>Visual: Family farming, fishing, and harvesting.</em></td>
      <td>Livelihoods in this region depend on ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Stakeholder</strong></td>
      <td>Any person or group affected by or able to influence the land plan. Includes farmers, Indigenous communities, conservation groups, government, downstream users. <em>Visual: Multiple figures around a planning table.</em></td>
      <td>The stakeholders in this plan include ___, ___, and ___.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">🛠️ In-class pre-teach activity (12 min)</div>
  <p><strong>Map sketch.</strong> I will give you a blank 10×10 grid representing 100 km². Sketch a land-use allocation: which cells are forest, crop, agroforestry, conservation, etc. Label using at least 6 vocabulary terms. We will compare allocations.</p>
</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">💬 Paired discussion prompt</div>
  <p>With a partner: each of you proposes one trade-off in your sketched plan. Defend why your trade-off is acceptable. Your partner challenges from the perspective of one stakeholder who LOSES in your plan.</p>
</div>

